Anonymous Fri 13 Sep 2024 18:09:52 No.69119982 Report

>>69118878
>I want a scifi setting where there's dozens of human empires with varied ideologies, aesthetics and cultures while there is also a variety of alien empires as well.

Traveller. https://www.freelancetraveller.com/index.html

The official setting's "known space" is a 1600 light year across blob in the galaxy, in the far future. There are human polities large and small. There are several starfaring alien races, including genetically engineered anthro wolves--not cute, cuddly, or especially friendly to humans, though. The setting is big enough and its established history is long enough that the GM can say "never mind all that stuff, our campaign is set in this star cluster twenty thousand light years away. Several centuries back a human colonization ship's jump drive malfunctioned and instead of Lambda Serpentis they ended up on the opposite side of the galaxy with no way home. Fortunately they found a star system with livable planets and founded a colony..." The galaxy is a big place. You want a setting with no ayylmaos, you can do that. You want to be the ayylmaos instead, you can do that too.

You do have to deal with a baked in "Age of Sail" feeling. Faster-than-light travel exists. Faster-than-light communication doesn't, except in the form of courier ships carrying messages. Faster-than-light travel in this setting is really gimped, with it taking weeks in hyperspace to jump just a handful of light-years. The very rarest, bleeding-edge military vessels, of which even interstellar empires can't afford to build more than a few, still can't go more than twenty light-years at a jump. Also the infantry may wear spacesuits but they're still mainly using guns that shoot metal projectiles using nitrocellulose propellant, because lasers small enough to be man-portable and powerful enough to be useful weapons are extremely expensive and not much better. It's very dieselpunk-in-space. I like it. Your mileage may vary.
